Added transient commandsAdded a new class that adds a wp transient command. The command takes get, set and delete, which correspond with get_transient, set_transient and delete_transient, respectively. Additionally, a fourth command, type, indicates whether the transients API is using the database or object cache for storage.n

Added commands for the WordPress object cache.This commit adds commands for interacting with the WordPress object cache. For each public function in for the WordPress object cache, a corresponding command has been created. Additionally, a which command has been written that attempts to determine which 3rd party object cache the current installation is implementing.n

Introduce system editor function in WP_CLIUtilsAdds a function called `launch_editor_for_input()` which launches thensystem's editor to allow file editing of post content, etc. Shouldnaccount for system line-endings properly, but probably needs testing onnWindows to be sure. Function returns false if no change (ie user :q!'snout of vim), or updated content if any change is made.nnAlso adds two new subcommands to `wp post`:n- `wp post create --edit`tLaunches the editor to build the postntttttttcontent before creating post.n- `wp post edit <id>`ttEdits post <id>'s content in system editor.n

Use WP_CLI::launch to open editorAlso use wp_tempnam to create file, and give the created file anmeaningful name rather than just using system or php's tempfile name.n

Handle error caused by reading empty file`fread()` will throw an error if trying to read an empty file (ie ifnuser deleted all post content or quit the editor on `wp post create`.nDetect that and fail gracefully.n

Use file_put_contents/file_get_contents instead of fwrite/freadMuch simpler this way. Also does away with the need to check for emptynoutput, although now we have to check the return value ofn`launch_editor_for_input` strictly against false, since its possible fornit to return an empty string now (editing a post and deleting all thencontent).n

Exit on end-of-fileIt's a common practice shells to exit on end-of-file. WP-CLI doesn't donthis.nnI traced the reason to the fact we're not checking the exit code fromnthe `read` builtin. If it timeouts or receives end-of-file, it'snnon-zero. In both these cases it makes sense to exit.n

Also, its possible that commands using the editornfunction will go on to perform other actions.)nnAlso, whitespace cleanup and minor refactoring... making a helpernmethod `_edit()` in post.php to make editor functions more reusable.n

Only use maintenance mode if a plugin or theme needs updatingWhen updating plugins (wp plugin update-all) or themes (wp theme update-all) on a WordPress multisite installation, maintenance activated and deactivated even if there are no updates to install.nnThe Plugin_Upgrader::bulk_upgrade() and Theme_Upgrader::bulk_upgrade() WordPress functions currently don't check that the array passed to it isn't empty, causing maintenance mode to be enabled even if no updates are required.nnThis bug doesn't affect non multisite installs, because for non multisite installs the code in Plugin_Upgrader::bulk_upgrade() and Theme_Upgrader::bulk_upgrade() only uses maintenance mode if the plugin/theme being updated is activated.nnFixes #491n

Incorporate author mapping support into the WordPress importer.* If a .csv filename is specified, it will look for an author mapping file.n* If the .csv author mapping file doesn't exist, it will create one for you and wait for you to edit.n* `--authors=create` will create any missing users, and expect that either user_email or user_logins map up directly.n* `--authors=skip` will ignore any byline mapping.n
Refactor author mapping code so it can be used with other importers
Make the `--authors` argument required. It's a very necessary step, even if just to have the user confirm they're skipping mappings.

Improve `theme install` logic to support force-installing a specific version.Previous `theme install` logic:nn* Updates the theme if there's an update available.n* Installs if the theme isn't installed.n* Otherwise, assume the theme is installed.nnNew `theme install` logic:nn* Don't do anything if theme is already installed and no `--version` specified.n* If `--version` is set and is different than what's installed, force install.n* Install if the theme isn't installed.n

Bug fix: allow plugins and themes to be installed from zip file URLs that contain GET parametersWithout this bug fix, doing something like:nwp plugin install http://downloads.wordpress.org/plugin/buddypress.1.7.2.zip?testnwould fail, because wp-cli wouldn't recognise that the URL contains a zip file. This is because the wp-cli code assumes that .zip are the last 4 characters in the URL.nnWith this bug fix, the .zip file detection in URLs has been improved, so the above command works as expected.nnThis allows (for example), plugins/themes to be installed directly from private Amazon S3 URLs (which have GET parameters in the URLs). For example:nnwp plugin install 'http://s3.amazonaws.com/bucketname/plugin.zip?AWSAccessKeyId=123&Expires=456&Signature=abcdef'nnNote: for complex URLs that contain ampersands, it is usually necessary to enclose the URL in single quotes.n

sanitize option before checking value equalityIf a plugin defines a sanitize_option filter, the equality check in 'wpnoption update' may indicate that the the new option value is differentnfrom the original when in fact it is not. Honor https scheme on --url optionWhen using the --url global option (or during core install), URLs with an https scheme were being treated as http.rnrnThe WP is_ssl() function checks for the $_SERVER['HTTPS'] flag or port 443 being set. This change allows standard and non-standard ports to be used so is_ssl() will return true when the supplied URL has an https scheme. This helps with the wp_guess_url() call during wp_install() so the proper URL is used when populating the database.

Improve plugin vs. theme detection for the error generated when the requested version of a plugin or theme does not existPreviously, the alter_api_response function would check for the substring 'theme' in the URL returned by the WordPress repository API. When requesting a non-existant version of a plugin such as Easy Updates Manager (which has the slug 'stops-core-theme-and-plugin-updates'), this would incorrectly report that the requested version of the _theme_ could not be found.nnThis change makes the substring test stricter, by expecting the URL to contain the string '/theme/' for themes. It also performs a similar check for plugins ('/plugin/'), and if both checks fail, it will produce a more generic response (e.g. Can't find the requested plugin/theme's version...)n

Move `--skip-themes` feature to a filter, instead of wp-settings hackIntroduces `Runner->add_wp_hook()` and `Runner->remove_wp_hook()` fornadding actions and filters before `add_filter()` is defined.nnTo ensure child themes can be skipped from loading, the `stylesheet`nvalue is always checked.nnFilter is added late on `setup_theme` hook to noop TEMPLATEPATH andn`STYLESHEETPATH`, and then removed early on `after_setup_theme` tonensure use of `get_template_directory()` still works as expected. Unfortunately,nthe downside is that the constants are defined incorrectly in this request,nbut hopefully this is an acceptable cost to the value of `--skip-themes`.n
Merge pull request #2944 from wp-cli/2278-skip-themes-filterMove `--skip-themes` feature to a filter, instead of wp-settings hack
Adds support for PHP 5.5 Memcache extension

Move `--skip-plugins` feature to a filter, instead of wp-settings hackFilters are added before the bootstrap process, to noopn`wp_get_active_network_plugins()` andn`wp_get_active_and_valid_plugins()`, and then removed early onn`plugins_loaded` to ensure later use of `get_option( 'active_plugins'n);` works as expected.nnUnfortunately, `get_options( 'active_plugins' );` will be inaccurate onnthe `muplugins_loaded` hook. Hopefully this will be an acceptable costnto being able to continue using `--skip-plugins`.n

Introduce `WP_CLI_STRICT_ARGS_MODE` for dealing with arg ambiguityConsider a command like:nn```nwp widget add rss sidebar-1 1 --url=http://wp-cli.org/feed/n```nnHistorically, the `--url=<url>` parameter has been treated like a globalnruntime argument, which has meant a command can't easily use it as itsnown. Now, using the `WP_CLI_STRICT_ARGS_MODE` will tell WP-CLI to treatnany arguments before the command as global, and after the command asnlocal.nnFor instance:nn```nWP_CLI_STRICT_ARGS_MODE=1 wp --url=wp.dev/site2 widget add rss sidebar-1 1n--url=http://wp-cli.org/feed/n```nnIn this example, `--url=wp.dev/site2` is the global argument, settingnWP-CLI to run against 'site2' on a WP multisite install.n`--url=http://wp-cli.org/feed/` is the local argument, setting the RSSnfeed widget with the proper URL.nnI've thought long and hard about making a breaking change, and enforcingnstrict args mode by default. At this point, I don't think it will evernbe worth it, given the majority use case isn't impacted by it, and it'sna better user experience to be able to supply arguments in an ambigiousnorder. When you need to be strict, you can use the environment variable.n

Add command hooks mechanism for simple dependency resolution.The following hooks have been added:nn1. `before_add_command:<command>` - Called before WP_CLI tries to add the command `<command>` to its known vocabulary.nnThe callback that is being called by this hook will receive an instance of a `WP_CLIDispatcherCommandAddition` object, which allows the callback to control whether WP_CLI should proceed with the addition or not. On aborting, the callback can provide a reason.nnThis can be used to let the addition of a command depend on some prior requirement to be met.nn2. `after_add_command:<command>` - Called after the command `<command>` has been added to the known vocabulary.nnThis can be used for let the addition of the command depend on other commands being added first. In this way, the addition of commands can be rendered independent of loading order.nnNote: Introducing the class `WP_CLIDispatcherCommandAddition` was necessary in order to get around the fact that arguments cannot be reliably passed across the flow `do_hook()` -> `call_user_func_array()` -> `add_hook()`.nnFixes #3835n

Defer command additions for sub-commands until their parent has been registered.If a sub-command is being added, this addition will be deferred when its parent is not yet registered. This is done by hooking the actual addition up to the `after_add_command:$parent` hook.nnThe list of deferred commands is stored to keep track of commands for which the parent hook is never called. This is the case for commands that provide a nested sub-command only, like `wp network meta`.nnThe bootstrap process has an additional step `RegisterDeferredCommands` that goes through the list of outstanding commands and adds them, as there's no opportunity for the parent being registered at this point.nnFixes #4084n

Fix autoloading from within a Phar.The Phar autoloading does not need any special case handling anymore. For any installation variation, the autoloaders are either in `WP_CLI_ROOT/vendor` or in `WP_CLI_ROOT/../../vendor`.nnFixes https://github.com/wp-cli/package-command/issues/12n

Adapt --ssh flag to work with Docker and Docker Compose.- Introduce a new `<scheme>:` prefix to the connection string providedn  to `--ssh`. Current accepted values are `docker:`, `docker-compose:`,n  and `ssh:`. This prefix can be omitted and a default of `ssh:` will ben  assumed.nn- Additionally make the `<user>@` option an explicit value separate fromn  `<host>` so that it can be passed via CLI flag to Docker processes.nn- Refactor the `Runner#run_ssh_command` method to respond to differentn  schemes.nn- Update existing functional test to accept escaped output. CS: Unexclude ValidFunctionName checksOnly one function, and three methods, were found to be violating the preferred WPCS naming conventions, so these lines have been excluded.nnWhile it does mean that the rest of the function signature line is also excluded from other checks, this seems like less of an issue than excluded the whole check from the rest of the project, which may allow other incorrectly named functions and methods to be accidentally introduced.nnOnce https://github.com/squizlabs/PHP_CodeSniffer/issues/604 is addressed, this ignores should be able to target just the specific check of the function / method name.n

Avoid global variable variablehttp://php.net/manual/en/migration70.incompatible.php#migration70.incompatible.variable-handling.global shows that variable variables can no longer be used with the `global` keyword for PHP 7.0 or later. The curly brace syntax can be used to emulate the previous behaviour.n
Case mismatch in function/method callMethod call does not respect case of method declaration.n
Fix parameters number mismatch declaration`WP_CLI::warning()` only accepts a single parameter.n

Define missing access modifiers for methodsOf itself, the changes here shouldn't have much impact, but it allows future code to be inspected / checked to ensure that access modifiers are explicitly defined.n
Fix dynamic methods invocation via ::Non-static methods should not usually be called via `::`, but as a method call on an object / `$this`.n
Use increment operationPre-increment can perform better than post-increment.n
Use short syntax for combined operator
Avoid unnecessary double quotesWill help to unify code style. Does not give any performance gain.n
Remove unnecessary paretheses

Use binary-safe fopenFrom official documentation:nnThe default translation mode depends on the SAPI and version of PHP that you are using, so you are encouraged to always specify the appropriate flag for portability reasons.nnFor portability, it is strongly recommended that you always use the 'b' flag when opening files with fopen().n

Use mt_rand() instead of rand()From official documentation:nnThe `mt_rand()` function is a drop-in replacement for the older `rand()`. It uses a random number generator with known characteristics using the u00c2u00bb Mersenne Twister, which will produce random numbers four times faster than what the average libc `rand()` provides.n
Unhide default value from else branchImproves readability.n
Remove redundant one-time use variable

Remove redundant else keywordCertain if-else conditions can have their else clause removed without changing the semantic. Generally, this is because the preceeding `if` clause returns, continues, breaks, exits or throws.n
Avoid using alias functions- `fputs()` is an alias of `fwrite()`n- `is_writeable()` is an alias of `is_writable()`n
Use type castingType casting can be up to 6 times faster.n
Fix sprintf() argument count mismatchOnly one placeholder, but two arguments provided.n
Improve randomness / uniqueness of uniqid()

Check if ABSPATH constant is defined before defining ABSPATHIf a `wp-cli.yml` has a _require_ in which the ABSPATH is defined wp-cli command will throw a notice.nExample:nn`wp-cli.yaml`nnrequire:n - abspath.phpnn`abspath.php`nn<?phpnif ( ! defined( 'ABSPATH' ) ) {ntdefine( 'ABSPATH', dirname( __FILE__ ) . '/custom_path/wp/' );n}nnWhen would you want this? In short symlinks, if you include WordPress in a symlink.nnWordPress tries to define the ABSPATH it uses wp-load.php and if it's in a symlink it will define the path baed on the actual location. Not the symlink path.nThat will give a problem if the wp-config.php is one directory above wp-load.php.n

PHPCS: fix up the code base [4] - remove redundant functionThis code doesn't add any value as the parent version would have been called anyway.n
PHPCS: fix up the code base [5] - yoda conditionsFixes relate to the following rules:n* Use Yoda conditions.n
PHPCS: fix up the code base [8] - assignments in conditionsFixes relate to the following rules:n* No assignments in conditions.n
PHPCS: fix up the code base [9] - function calls in for conditionThe `$link_count` is not going to change during the loop, so there is no need to repeatedly call `count()`.n
PHPCS: fix up the code base [11] - use selfFixes relate to the following rules:n* Use `self` when referencing a (static) class member from within the same class.n

PHPCS: fix up the code base [12] - assignment within function callPHP does not have a concept of named parameters, so assigning a parameter being passed in a function call to a variable within that call does not have a function, especially if that variable is not used anywhere within the same function (as it isn't in these cases).n

PHPCS: fix up the code base [13] - assignments in conditionsFixes relate to the following rules:n* No assignments in conditions.nnWhere there was no doubt about what the possible output types could be, I've also adjusted the conditions from loose comparisons to strict.n

PHPCS: fix up the code base [14] - assignments in conditionsFixes relate to the following rules:n* No assignments in conditions.nnAs this was an assignment in an `elseif`, the logic of the code needed some tweaking as well to turn the `elseif` into an `if`.n

PHPCS: fix up the code base [17] - require vs includeWhen an include fails, you'll receive a `warning` and PHP will try to continue execution. When a `require` fails, this causes a fatal error, which considering this statement is trying to load the main file, is more appropriate.n

PHPCS: fix up the code base [3] - strict comparisonsFixes relate to the following rules:n* Use strict comparisons.n* Use the `$strict` parameter when calling `in_array()`.nnNote: as there were quite a few occurances of this in this codebase: please remember that _strings_, generally speaking, have the lowest precedence when doing a loose comparison, i.e. the string will be juggled and this can lead to _**very**_ unexpected results.nThink `if ( 0 == 'text' ) { print 'success!'; } // Result: success!`.nSo, while using strict comparisons should be the rule anyway, it is all the more important when doing comparisons involving strings.n

PHP 7.0+: allow for changed list assignment orderThe variables which are problematic are in actual fact not used in the code, but this was not clear just by looking at it.nnBy making the variables names more descriptive and unique, the PHP 7.0 issue is bypassed and the code is better auto-documented.n

PHPCS: fix up the code base [1] - whitespaceSimple, mostly whitespace related, fixes to make the code comply with the WPCliCS rules.nnFixes relate to the following rules:n* Align the equality operators in assignment blocks.n* No multiple assignments in one statement.n* One space between a control structure keyword and the open parenthesis.n* No space between a function call/language contruct keyword and the open parenthesis.n* One space on the inside of open/close parenthesis when there is content between them.n* Always use parenthesis when instantiating a new object.n* One space after equality operators.n* One space before and after concatenation operators.n* Don't use concatenation when it isn't necessary.n* There should be no space before a comma.n* Associative arrays with more than one item, should be multi-line.n* The double arrow in multi-line arrays should be aligned.n* Each array item in a multi-line array should be followed by a comma.n* Use single quoted strings when the string doesn't contain a single quote or variables.n* There should be one blank line after a namespace statement.n* Use tabs for indentation, spaces for inline alignment.n* Files should end on a new line character.n
PHPCS: fix up the code base [16] - operator precedenceUse brackets to prevent confusion over operator precedence.n

PHPCS: fix up the code base [2] - scope modifiersFixes relate to the following rules:n* Always specify visibility for all class properties and methods.n

PHPCS: fix up the code base [7] - closure declarationWhether a full-blown function or a closure, the body of a function has to start on a new line, once indented and the close brace has to be on its own line.nnAs this would make the function call in which this closure was wrapped multi-line, I've moved the closure declaration to a variable declared before the function call and pass the variable in instead.n

Avoid double registration of commandsWhen a given subcommand is already found:n- if it is a command namespace, we replace it with the new command, and attach all children of the namespace to the new command.n- if it is a regular command, we skip registration, to avoid double registration. This means only the first registration counts (making overrides through packages and requires precede bundled commands).nnFixes #5186n

Composer: use wp-cli-tests ^2.1... as that version contains the new WP_CLI_CS PHPCS standard.nnIncludes updating the `composer.lock` file with `composer update wp-cli/wp-cli-tests --with-all-dependencies` which resulted in the following updates:n```n  - Removing phpcompatibility/phpcompatibility-wp (1.0.0)n  - Updating wp-coding-standards/wpcs (1.2.1 => 2.1.0): Loading from cachen  - Updating wp-cli/eval-command (v2.0.3 => v2.0.4): Loading from cachen  - Updating wp-cli/config-command (v2.0.2 => v2.0.3): Loading from cachen  - Updating phpcompatibility/php-compatibility (8.2.0 => 9.1.1): Loading from cachen  - Removing wp-cli/wp-cli-tests (v2.0.13)n  - Installing wp-cli/wp-cli-tests (v2.1.1): Loading from cachen  - Updating roave/security-advisories (dev-master 9c6c45a => dev-master 1b329f4)n```n

.gitignore: ignore correct phpcs/phpunit config files* Remove refs which shouldn't be in this file.n- The `phpunit.xml.dist` file shouldn't be ignored.n- The two directory entries look like personal ones which shouldn't have gotten into the `.gitignore` file in the first place, but should have been put into someone's personal `.git/info/exclude` file.n* Add files which allow devs to overwrite config files for PHPUnit and PHPCSn- The `.dist` files should be committed. However, for their personal use, devs can overrule those files with versions without `.dist`.nThose personal versions should never be committed.nnAs a side-note: for PHPCS, having a personal version while still using the original `.dist` file is made very easy, as you can just import the `.dist` file as a starting point, like so:n```xmln<?xml version=1.0?>n<ruleset name=WP-CLI>n<rule ref=./phpcs.xml.dist/>n</ruleset>n```n
